  "narrative": {
    "intro": "NAICS 336611 (Ship Building and Repairing) has $15.2B in contract obligations in FY2026 to date. Award activity so far includes 4,056 awards with an average award size of $3.8M. Obligations are down 59.0% year over year. Historical annual obligations show variability across recent fiscal years: FY21 was $20.7B, FY22 was $22.3B, FY23 was $26.9B, FY24 was $24.2B, and FY25 was $37.2B. The Department of Defense accounts for the largest share of FY2026 to date obligations at $10.7B, followed by the Department of Homeland Security at $4.2B. Other buying agencies with FY2026 to date obligations include the Department of Commerce at $144M, the Department of Transportation at $54.1M, and the Department of State at $34M. Top performing vendors in FY2026 to date include HUNTINGTON INGALLS INC ($2.6B), HUNTINGTON INGALLS INCORPORATED ($1.9B), NATIONAL STEEL AND SHIPBUILDING COMPANY ($1.9B), and ELECTRIC BOAT CORPORATION ($1.5B). The market concentration among a few large vendors and the dominance of the Department of Defense are clear in the FY2026 to date data.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How has the NAICS 336611 market trended recently?",
        "body": "Obligations are down 59.0% year over year in FY2026 to date. Annual obligations ranged from $20.7B in FY21 to $37.2B in FY25, with FY26 at $15.2B so far. The FY2026 to date total of $15.2B represents a notable decline from the prior-year peak of $37.2B in FY25. Yearly volatility is evident across FY21–FY25 and into FY26 to date."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Who are the main buyers and suppliers in FY2026 to date?",
        "body": "The Department of Defense is the largest buyer with $10.7B in obligations, followed by the Department of Homeland Security at $4.2B. Other agencies with material FY2026 to date obligations include the Department of Commerce ($144M) and the Department of Transportation ($54.1M). Leading vendors by obligations are HUNTINGTON INGALLS INC ($2.6B), HUNTINGTON INGALLS INCORPORATED ($1.9B), and NATIONAL STEEL AND SHIPBUILDING COMPANY ($1.9B)."
      }
    ]
  },
